The Constitution has not been amended. It has been violated, and then quietly treated as if it changed.

Nowhere is this betrayal more dangerous than with the war power.

Article I is unambiguous: the power to declare war belongs to Congress, and to Congress alone. The framers placed it there deliberately. They had lived under a king who could take a nation to war by personal decree. They built a republic so no single person could do the same.

But they did not stop at text. They feared the instrument as much as the authority.

The founders viewed standing armies with profound suspicion, not because they doubted military necessity, but because they understood what a permanent armed force in the hands of a single executive would become: a tool of ambition, a means of war without deliberation, and eventually the private army of whoever held power. James Madison warned that standing armies were "dangerous to liberty." Elbridge Gerry declared that standing armies in peacetime are "the bane of liberty." The Anti-Federalists made opposition to permanent military forces a centerpiece of their critique.

The design was deliberate: Congress would control the purse and the power to declare war. The military would be called into being for specific purposes, then disbanded. No president would have a permanent force at his disposal, ready to deploy on his word alone.

That design has been abandoned.

The United States now maintains the largest standing military in its history, deployed across the globe, available at presidential command, and used repeatedly without congressional authorization. The founders' structural safeguard has been dismantled. The army they feared would become an instrument of executive will has become exactly that.

Yet over decades, presidents have initiated military action without congressional consent. Congress has watched and said nothing. Courts have refused to intervene. And from that collective failure, a dangerous fiction has emerged: that presidential war-making is now constitutional because it has gone unchallenged for so long.

That is not how constitutional law works. That is how constitutional law dies.

Article I powers cannot be waived by neglect. They can be altered only by amendment, by the explicit consent of the people, through the process the Constitution itself prescribes. Inaction does not transfer authority. Silence does not repeal text. Habit does not override law.

What has changed is not the Constitution. What has changed is our willingness to enforce it, and the cowardice of those whose duty it is to do so.

Repeated violations have been laundered into precedent. Tolerated breaches have been rebranded as authorization. Custom has been permitted to masquerade as legality. This is not evolution of law. It is dereliction. It is complicity. It is the quiet betrayal of an oath.

The claim that it would now be "unfair" to insist on congressional authorization, because presidents have acted unilaterally for decades, turns the Constitution on its head. The unfairness is not in enforcing the rule late. The unfairness is in permitting power to profit from its own lawlessness.

If neglect can rewrite the Constitution, then no amendment is ever needed. Power needs only patience. Limits disappear not by repeal, but by exhaustion, not by argument, but by attrition.

This is precisely what the framers feared.

James Madison warned that liberty is endangered not by dramatic seizure but by "gradual and silent encroachments," the slow migration of power from where the Constitution placed it to where ambition wants it. The war power has migrated. Not by amendment. Not by consent. By silence, by cowardice, by the failure of every institution charged with preventing exactly this.

Thomas Jefferson foresaw the destination. He called it "elective despotism": a government chosen by the people but no longer restrained by them. A president who commands a global military and deploys it without Congress is not a chief executive. He is an elected monarch exercising the very power the Constitution was written to forbid.

Benjamin Franklin offered the darkest warning of all. On the final day of the Constitutional Convention, he predicted the republic would be "well administred for a Course of Years" but would "end in Despotism as other Forms have done before it, when the People shall become so corrupted as to need Despotic Government, being incapable of any other."

Franklin did not warn against tyrants. He warned against us.

That is why constitutional ignorance is not innocent. In a republic, the people are the final check. If citizens do not read the Constitution, do not understand why powers were separated, do not grasp why ambition was made to counter ambition, they cannot recognize when those limits are breached. They become not the guardians of liberty but the instruments of its destruction. A Constitution unknown to the people is a Constitution easily discarded by their rulers.

The text still says what it has always said. The president cannot take the nation to war without the explicit consent of Congress. Not a word has changed.

What has changed is us.

A Congress that will not assert its power. Courts that will not enforce the limits. Citizens who do not know the document they claim to revere. And a political class that treats the Constitution as ornament, invoked for applause, ignored when inconvenient.

The founders tried to prevent this twice: once by reserving the war power to Congress, and once by warning against the standing army that would make its abuse possible. We have undone both. We gave presidents a permanent military. Then we stopped asking permission for its use.

This is not constitutional evolution. It is constitutional rot, the slow decay of self-government by a people who no longer demand it.

Neglect is not consent.

It is surrender.
